All these specimens were from a patch of about 25-40 mushrooms, all extremely similar. These had no distinct odor or taste. They bruised blue at a moderate pace. All had the yellow margin around cap. As you can see, there is some very fine reticulation at the top of stipe. These had a redder cap than the L. pseudosensibilis I usually find in this area.

Because they are missing the characteristic odor, and because they didn’t bruise blue so quickly, I think L pseudosensibilis is most likely. But reticulation and the redness of the cap suggest sensibilis instead.

results.notes:
A single fruitbody growing in short grass/moss an open space surrounded by old oaks. These warts mean business! :-) I will take a look at the spores later to propose a species name.
There are four recognized phylogenetic Strobilomyces species in the USA (Han et al. study, 2020), two of which are unnamed (both from the southeast). The other two are S. confusus and S. strobilaceus. It’s interesting to read about the latter one in the paper (text in bold is marked by me):
“The concept of S. strobilaceus was taxonomically not clarified yet due to the absence of original type material. Petersen et al. (2012) designated a neotype specimen (SAV 3214) collected in Slovakia and suggested that only one species occurs in Europe. In the S. strobilaceus subclade, there are two strongly supported lineages: one consisted of seven collections from Europe and East Asia, and the other lineage had four collections from North/Central America and East Asia. We observed no obvious morphological differences among these samples except for the variable shape of pileal scales. Based on the criteria of the GCPSR method applied in this study, the S. strobilaceus subclade is recognized here as a single phylogenetic species. Future analyses could possibly compromise the monophyly of the two lineages by the addition of more samples.” — Han et al. (2020)
Comparison of ITS sequences from these two lineages revealed that the accessions from the USA are only 91% similar to the European ones. I looked at the alignments and still don’t understand why the European strobilaceus is conspecific with the North American entity.

results.notes:
Habitat: on the ground in dark and damp, predominantly deciduous and rhododendron woods
Cap: diameter 7 cm, dry, dull, smooth, brick red without a marginal color change, not cracking but red where cracked, slight sterile margin. Not bruising blue
Tubes & Pores: small, not elongated near stipe, dull yellow, bruising quickly blue.
Stalk: 67 mm long and 19 mm thick, equal, dry, no reticulation, ground color dull yellow with a few small rosy exceptions near apex, covered almost entirely by a fine tomentum-like surface that does not seem to have been yellow or reddish at first. No basal mycelium evident
Flesh: dense and firm, whitish in the cap, yellowing slightly in the stipe, bruising quickly but lightly blue.
Odor and taste: no distinct odor, taste slightly and slowly acidic
Spores: thin deposit, probably olive brown

Photos also available at https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/31052937. Collected by a participant in the Ohio Mushroom Society’s 2019 summer foray. Collected in a hardwood forest. Trees present in the area were Acer spp., Quercus spp., Ulmus spp., Carya spp., Fagus grandifolia, Ostrya virginiana and other hardwoods present in the area. Base of stem staining blue-green. Context staining red.

results.notes: All mushrooms came from a large horse manure pile. The mushrooms grew in clumps ranging from 2 to 6. The darker color present on some caps stems from spore deposits of larger specimens. The sizes vary slightly with a range of 3-6 inches tall, with a few smaller individuals. Cap sizes range from .75-2in in diameter, again with some smaller individuals present. Specimens range in color from light tan to dark brown with stems that are whiteish tan near the cap, and darken to deep brown near the base. Each specimens stem has vertical lines that run the entire length. The stems are hollow and fibrous. Spore prints are jet black. I am very much an amateur so Im sorry if my notes arent good. One thing that throws me off is the dry peeling appearance of some of the caps, I have seen this before on past fruitings in the same manure pile and it throws me off each time.
This specimen has white, unchaging lates that is very acrid.

results.notes: Several collected at this NJMA foray. The ones with cap not zonate developed sulfur yellow staining where gills were sliced. Others that we thought may also be L. croceus but with zonate cap (not pictured) did not exhibit the yellow stain on cut gills. I’m wondering if the staining may be a trait associated with young fruit bodies and the concentric bands of orange/yellow something that develops post maturity. The zonate ones were larger and emitted very little latex.
